President Donald Trump has proclaimed April 2 to April 8, 2017, as National Crime Victims' Rights Week. In the proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of supporting crime victims and their families, as well as the need to find effective solutions to crime. President Trump mentions the establishment of the Victims of Crime Act in 1984, which created the Crime Victims Fund to provide compensation for crime-related expenses and support victims' service programs. He also highlights the development of the Victims Of Immigration Crime Engagement (VOICE) office within the Department of Homeland Security to assist victims of crimes committed by criminal aliens. The proclamation concludes with a call to renew the commitment to protecting all victims of crime and upholding law and order.